### Writing to Files

The `ofstream` class is used for writing data to files.

---

### Basic Writing

```cpp
#include <fstream>

ofstream file("output.txt");

if (file.is_open()) {
  file << "Hello, World!" << endl;
  file << "The answer is " << 42 << endl;
  file.close();
}
```

---

### Writing Different Data Types

```cpp
ofstream file("data.txt");

int age = 25;
double salary = 50000.50;
string name = "Alice";

file << name << " " << age << " " << salary << endl;
```

---

### Append Mode

```cpp
ofstream file("log.txt", ios::app);  // Append, don't overwrite
file << "New log entry" << endl;
file.close();
```

---

### Binary Writing

```cpp
#include <fstream>

struct Record {
  int id;
  double value;
};

Record rec = {1, 99.5};
ofstream file("data.bin", ios::binary);
file.write(reinterpret_cast<char*>(&rec), sizeof(rec));
```

---

### Error Checking

```cpp
ofstream file("output.txt");
if (file.fail()) {
  cout << "Failed to open file";
  return 1;
}

file << "Data";
if (file.bad()) {
  cout << "Write error occurred";
}
```

---

> **Key Point:** By default, `ofstream` truncates (overwrites) existing files. Use `ios::app` to append. Always check that the file opened successfully.

codeExample:
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
using namespace std;

int main() {
  ofstream file("students.txt");

  if (!file) {
    cout << "Error opening file" << endl;
    return 1;
  }

  file << "Name,Grade,Age" << endl;
  file << "Alice,A,20" << endl;
  file << "Bob,B,22" << endl;
  file << "Charlie,A-,21" << endl;

  file.close();
  cout << "Data written to students.txt" << endl;
  return 0;
}
